issue.title: Replace longest path with closest hamiltonian cycle
issue.body:
If a hamiltonian cycle doesn't exist, we should try to find the closest hamiltonian cycle, defined as a hamiltonian cycle created by adding an edge between two nodes that are not already connected by an edge directed in either direction. e.g.
```
A -> B -> C
```
Doesn't have a hamiltonian cycle, but the closest hamiltonian cycle is
```
A -> B -> C (->) A
```
since neither `(C,A)` nor `(A,C)` are currently in the graph.

We should then render these close edges differently to indicate that these edges do not exist yet

issue.title: Document find_cycles
issue.body:
Add to `find_cycles` docstring describing the algorithm being used.

Are we using DFS? What's wrong running DFS on every vertex to find all the cycles the given vertex is in? It would make the code a lot cleaner if we just use DFS (http://codereview.stackexchange.com/a/78603)

issue.title: Display multiple cycles
issue.body:
This includes 2 different cases:

A) display all the other cycles we find in a graph along with the biggest ones

B) display all cycles that tie for the max-length cycle. (if we don't end up implementing this, maybe we should predetermine which cycle shows up?)

I think we could do neither or one of these, but not both, since too many things would probably overlap. What do you guys think?

issue.title: Collect data on previous games
issue.body:
Since Sportradar doesn't have past data, find data on internet for previous games ([wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_Pac-12_Conference_football_season) seems to be good, look at the schedule section) and make a JSON file of the form

```
[
    # for each game
    {
        'date': '1/1/2015',
        'winner': 'CAL' (see constants.py),
        'loser': 'USC',
        'winner_score': 10,
        'loser_score': 0,
    }
]
```

Then one of the collaborators will upload the data onto the Heroku server (and can be used for data on development servers)
